> **React Lifecycle methods** Lifecycle methods are custom functionality that gets executed during the different phases of a component. There are methods available when the component gets created and inserted into the DOM (mounting), when the component updates, and when the component gets unmounted or removed from the DOM.

### **Creation phase**

<span style={{color: '#ff00a9'}}>**constructor(props)**</span> method is called with the **props** as the arguments, and you should always start by calling the **super(props)** before anything else. This will initiate the parent’s constructor method and allow the component to inherit methods from its parent **(React.Component)**.  

*If you don’t initialise state and you don’t bind methods, you don’t need to implement a constructor for your React component.* 

<span style={{color: '#ff00a9'}}>**static getDerivedStateFromProps(props, state)**</span> This method is invoked right before calling the render method, both on the initial mount and on subsequent updates. It should return an object to update the state, or null to update nothing.  

<span style={{color: '#ff00a9'}}>**render**</span> This is the required method for every component. This method is invoked whenever **state** or **props** changes*,* and it has to re-render the HTML to the DOM with the new changes.  

<span style={{color: '#ff00a9'}}>**componentDidMount()**</span> is invoked immediately after a component is mounted (inserted into the tree). Initialization that requires DOM nodes should go here. If you need to load data from a remote endpoint, this is a good place to instantiate the API request.

### **Updating phase**

A component is updated whenever there is a change in the component’s state or props. React has five built-in methods that get called, in this order, when a component is updated:

1. **getDerivedStateFromProps**  
2. **shouldComponentUpdate**  
3. **render**  
4. **getSnapshotBeforeUpdate**  
5. **componentDidUpdate**

<span style={{color: '#ff00a9'}}>**shouldComponentUpdate()**</span> method can return a Boolean value that specifies whether React should continue with the rendering or not. In **PureComponent**, the **shouldComponentUpdate()** method is handled by default using shallow comparison of **state** and **props** against their previous values.

<span style={{color: '#ff00a9'}}>**getSnapshotBeforeUpdate()**</span> is invoked right before the most recently rendered output is committed to the DOM. It enables your component to capture some information from the DOM (e.g. scroll position) before it is potentially changed. Any value returned by this lifecycle will be passed as a parameter to **componentDidUpdate()**.

<span style={{color: '#ff00a9'}}>**componentDidUpdate()**</span> is invoked immediately after updating occurs. This method is not called for the initial render. You may call **setState()** immediately in **componentDidUpdate()**. Typically in **componentDidUpdate**, you wrap the logic in a conditional so that you don’t execute it on every **state** or **props** change.

### **UnMounting phase** 

> **UnMounting phase** The next phase in the life-cycle is when a component is removed from the DOM, or *unmounting* as it is named in React. React has only one built-in method that gets called when a component is unmounted. <span style={{color: '#ff00a9'}}>componentWillUnmount()</span> is invoked immediately before a component is unmounted and destroyed. Perform any necessary cleanup in this method, such as invalidating timers, cancelling network requests, or cleaning up any subscriptions that were created in <span style={{color: '#ff00a9'}}>componentDidMount()</span>.
> 

:::tip
You should not call **setState()** in **componentWillUnmount()** because the component will never be re-rendered.
